        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000570": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000570",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000150\">129</$link></sup> MS. 5.650 has the words in brackets.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000571": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000571",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000572": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000572",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000150\">130</$link></sup> Eden (p. 252) says of the strait: “<span>they founde the ſtraight nowe cauled the ſtraight of Magellanus, beinge in ſum place C.x. leagues in length: and in breadth ſumwhere very large and in other places lyttle more than halfe a league in bredth.</span>” Stanley (p. 57) is uncertain of the French <i>et quasi autant de largeur moins de demye lieue</i>, which is (translated freely) simply “something like almost a half-league wide.” The “Roteiro” (Stanley, p. 7) says that the channel “at some places has a width of three leagues, and two, and one, and in some places half a league.” Transylvanus (<span class=\"sc\">Vol. I</span>, p. 320) gives the width as two, three, five, or ten Italian miles; Gomara, two leagues or so; Barros, one league at the mouth, and the strait, from a musket or cannon shot to one and one and one-half leagues; Castanheda, at the mouth as wide as two ships close together, then opening up to one league; Peter Martyr, a sling-shot’s distance in places. (Mosto, p. 61, note 2.)</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000573": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000573",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000574": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000574",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000150\">131</$link></sup> <i>Proise</i> or <i>Proi</i> (<i>proy</i>, <i>proic</i>) is an ancient Catalonian word meaning the “bow moorings;” Cf. Jal, <i>Glossaire nautìque</i> (Mosto, p. 61, note 3). The old Spanish word is “proís,” which signifies both the thing to which the ship is moored ashore, and the rope by which it is moored to the shore.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000575": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000575",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000576": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000576",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000150\">132</$link></sup> This passage is as follows in MS. 5,650: “The said strait was a circular place surrounded with mountains (as I have said), and the majority of the sailors thought that there was no exit from it into the said Pacific Sea. But the captain-general declared that there was another strait which led out, and that he knew that well, for he had seen it on a marine chart of the king of Portugal. That map had been made by a renowned sailor and pilot, named Martin de Boesme. The said captain sent two of his ships forward—one named the ‘Sainct Anthoine,’ and the other the ‘Conception’—in order that they might look for and discover the exit from the said strait, which was called the cape de la Baya.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000577": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000577",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000578": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000578",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p>Martin de Behaim (Beham, Behem, Behemira, Behen, Bœhem), Bœhm) was born about 1459 (some say also in 1430 or 1436) of a family originally from Bohemia, in Nuremberg, Germany, and died at Lisbon, July 29, 1506. He was a draper in Flanders, 1477–1479, after which he went to Lisbon (1480) where he became <a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a>acquainted with Columbus. In 1484 he was chosen geographer of Diego Cam’s expedition to Western Africa. On his return, he received the order of knighthood in the military order of Christ of Portugal; after which he went to the island of Fayal in the Azores where he became interested in colonization and agriculture, and married the daughter of the governor. In 1491 he returned to Germany, where he lived at Nuremberg until 1493, and where, at the request of his townsmen, he constructed an immense globe on the information of Ptolemy, Strabo, and others, which contains many errors (see facsimile in Guillemard), In 1493 he returned to Lisbon, and in 1494 to Fayal, where he remained until 1506, when he went to Lisbon. Many myths sprung up about him, such that he had visited America before Columbus and the straits of Magellan before Magalhães, the latter of whom he may have known at Lisbon. See Rose, <i>New Biographical Dictionary</i> (London, 1848); <i>Grande Encyclopédie</i> (Paris, Lamirault et Cie.); and Guillemard, pp. 73, 74.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000579": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000579",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000580": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000580",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p>See Guillemard (<i>ut supra</i>, pp. 189–198) for a discussion of knowledge regarding the existence of a strait to the south of the American continent, prior to Magalhães’s discovery and passage of it. Guillemard, after weighing the evidence for and against, decides that there may have been a “more or less inexact knowledge of the existence of some antarctic break “that would allow access to the eastern world.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000581": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000581",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000582": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000582",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000150\">133</$link></sup> Possession Bay, according to Mosto, p. 61, note 5, but Guillemard (pp. 199, 200) thinks it may have been Lomas Bay.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000583": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000583",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000584": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000584",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000150\">134</$link></sup> Probably Anegada Point to the northwest of Cape Orange.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000585": {
