        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000594": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000594",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000150\">139</$link></sup> MS. 5,650 reads: “When near us they suddenly discharged a number of guns, whereat we very joyously saluted them with artillery and cries.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000595": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000595",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000596": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000596",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">140</$link></sup> The first is the passage east of Dawson Island, which extends to the northeast into Useless Bay and to the southeast into Admiralty Sound. The second opening was the passage between the western side of Dawson Island and Brunswick Peninsula.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000597": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000597",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000598": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000598",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">141</$link></sup> Esteban Gomez was an experienced Portuguese navigator and pilot with ambitions only less than those of Magalhães, his kinsman (Guillemard, p. 203). His desertion occurred probably <a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a>in the first part of November, and was perhaps directly due to pique at what he considered lack of appreciation from Magalhães. Conspiring with Gerónimo Guerra, the notary, who was elected captain of the “San Antonio” they made off with that ship, and after imprisoning Alvaro de Mezquita, returned to Spain, anchoring at Sevilla May 6, 1521. There Gomez was imprisoned after the return of the “Victoria,” but was liberated, and in 1524 proposed an expedition to discover a northwest passage. An expedition having been fitted out by Cárlos I, he coasted Florida and the eastern coast, as far as Cape Cod, and returned to Spain in 1525. See <i>Grande Encyclopédie</i>; Navarrete, iv, pp. 42–45, and 201–208; and Guillemard, <i>ut supra</i>, pp. 203–205.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000599": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000599",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000600": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000600",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p>Brito’s story of the exploration of the strait and the loss of the “San Antonio” (Navarrete, iv, pp. 307, 308) is as follows: “They left that place [<i>i.e.</i>, the river of Santa Cruz] on October 20, and went to enter a strait of which they had no knowledge. The entrance of the strait extends for about 15 leguas; and after they had entered, it seemed to them that it was all land-locked, and they accordingly anchored there. Magallanes sent a Portuguese pilot named Juan Carballo ashore with orders to ascend a mountain in order to ascertain whether there was any outlet. Carballo returned saying that it appeared land-locked to him. Thereupon Magallanes ordered the ships ‘San Antonio’ and the ‘Concepcion’ to go in advance in order to explore the strait. After having gone ahead for about 30 leguas, they returned to tell Magallanes that the river went farther but that they could not tell where it would take them. Upon receiving that information Magallanes weighed anchor with all three ships, and advanced along the strait until reaching the point to which the others had explored. Then he ordered the ‘San Antonio’ of which Alvaro de Mezquito, his cousin, was captain, and Esteban Gomez, a Portuguese pilot, to go ahead and explore a southern channel that opened in the strait. That ship did not return to the others and it is not known whether it returned to Castilla or whether it was wrecked. Magallanes proceeded with his remaining ships until he found an exit.” Correa’s account of the desertion of the “San Antonio” is as usual with him, inadequate, and evidently based on hearsay evidence (see Stanley, p. 250).</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000601": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000601",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000602": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000602",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">142</$link></sup> Literally “brother;” but to be understood probably as the expression <i>cugino germano</i>, “cousin german.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000603": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000603",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000604": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000604",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">143</$link></sup> MS. 5,650 begins this sentence as follows: “But that ship lost its time, for the other.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000605": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000605",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000606": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000606",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">144</$link></sup> Guillemard (p. 206) conjectures from the records of Albo, Pigafetta, and Herrera that the river of Sardines is Port Gallant which is located on the Brunswick Peninsula, opposite the Charles Islands. Albo (Navarrete, iv, p. 215) says that after taking the <a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a>course to the northwest they sailed about 15 leagues before anchoring.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000607": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000607",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000608": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000608",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">145</$link></sup> Albo (Navarrete, iv, p. 216) says that the two capes at the exit of the strait were called Fermosa and Deseado, this latter being Cape Pillar (see Guillemard, map facing p. 198).</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000609": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000609",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000610": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000610",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">146</$link></sup> MS. 5,650 adds: “which were on the other side.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000611": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000611",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000612": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000612",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">147</$link></sup> João Serrão, the brother of Magalhães’s staunchest friend Francisco Serrão, and a firm supporter of the great navigator. Pigafetta errs in calling him a Spaniard (see p. 183), though he may have become a naturalized Spaniard, since the register speaks of him as a citizen of Sevilla. One document (Navarrete, iv, p. 155) calls him a Portuguese pilot, and Brito (Navarrete, iv, p. 308) a Castilian. He was an experienced navigator and captain, and had served under Vasco da Gama, Almeida, and Albuquerque. Vasco da Gama (on his second voyage, 1502–1503) made him captain of the ship “Pomposa” which was built in Mozambique where he was left to attend to Portuguese affairs. On this expedition he saw the coast of Brazil for the first time, for Vasco da Gama’s fleet, ere doubling the Cape of Good Hope, crossed to the Brazilian coast, which they followed as far as Cape Santo Agostinho. He fought bravely in the battle of Cananor under Almeida (March 16, 1506, in which Magalhães also participated). He was chief captain of three caravels in August, 1510, in Eastern water, and was in the Java seas in 1512, but must have returned to Portugal soon after that, for he was there in 1513; although he seems to have been appointed clerk at the fortress of Calicut in the latter year. He embarked with Magalhães as captain and pilot of the “Santiago,” but after the wreck of that vessel near port San Julian was given command of the “Concepcion,” in which he later explored the strait. Failing to dissuade Magalhães from attacking the natives of Matan, he became commander, with Duarte Barbosa, of the fleet at Magalhães’s death, and was murdered by the Cebuans after the treacherous banquet given by them to the fleet. See Guillemard (<i>ut supra</i>), and Stanley’s <i>Three voyages of Vasco da Gama</i> (Hakluyt Society publications, London, 1869).</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000613": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000613",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000614": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000614",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">148</$link></sup> MS. 5,650 reads as follows: “Such was the method ordered by the captain from the beginning, in order that the ship that happened to become separated from the others might rejoin the fleet.” Then it adds: “Thereupon the crew of the said ship did what the captain had ordered them and more, for they set two banners with their letters,” etc.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000615": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000615",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000616": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000616",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">149</$link></sup> “The island of Santa Magdalena (Mosto, p. 62, note 11).</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000617": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000617",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000618": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000618",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">150</$link></sup> According to Guillemard the river of Isleo (or “of Islands”) <a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a>is located on Brunswick Peninsula, and is identified with the port of San Miguel, just east of the “River of Sardines;” the island where the cross was planted would be one of the Charles Islands.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000619": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000619",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000620": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000620",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">151</$link></sup> The “Roteiro” (Stanley, p. 3) mentions that the day at the port of San Julian was about seven hours long; while the anonymous Portuguese (Stanley, p. 30) says that the sun only appeared for some “four hours each day” in June and July. Transylvanus says the nights in the strait were not longer than five hours.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000621": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000621",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000622": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000622",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">152</$link></sup> MS. 5,650 adds: “which is the collateral wind between the east and south.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000623": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000623",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000624": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000624",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000157\">153</$link></sup> MS. 5,650 adds: “and anchorages.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000625": {
            "role": "text",
