        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001148": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001148",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">390</$link></sup> Albo (Navarrete, iv, p. 221) reads as follows when relating the course of the ships on leaving Cebú: “We left Subu and sailed southwest to a latitude of 9 and three-fourths degrees, between the end of Subu and an island called Bohol. Toward the western end of Subu lies another island, by name, Panilongo, which is inhabited by blacks. That island and Subu contain gold and considerable ginger. The former lies in 9 and one-third degrees and Subu in 10 and one-third degrees. Accordingly we left that channel and went 10 leguas south and anchored in the island of Bohol. There we made two ships of the three, burning the third, because we had no men. The last-named island lies in 9 and one-half degrees. We left Bohol and sailed southwest toward Quipit, and anchored at that settlement on the right hand side of a river. On the northwest and open side are two islets which lie in 8 and one-half degrees. We could get no food there, for the people had none, but we made peace with them. That island of Quipit contains a quantity of gold, ginger, and cinnamon. Accordingly, we determined to go in search of food. The distance from the headland of Quipit to the first islands is about 112 leguas. It and the islands lie in an east by north and south by west direction; and this island [<i>i.e.</i>, Mindanao] extends quite generally east and west.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001149": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001149",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001150": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001150",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p>The “Roteiro” (Stanley, p. 14) calls the port of Quipit (which is located on the northeastern coast of Mindanao) Capyam or Quype. Carvalho gave the boat of the burned ship to the inhabitants of that place. Brito (Navarrete, iv, p. 309) says that they learned the location of Borneo at Mindanao. Quipit becomes Gibith in Transylvanus, Chipico in Peter Martyr, and Quepindo in Barros (see Mosto, p. 84, note 2).</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001151": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001151",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001152": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001152",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">391</$link></sup> The first European mention of the island of Luzón. Luzón is derived from the Malay <i>lâsung</i> (Tagalog, <i>losong</i>), “mortar.” See Crawfurd’s <i>Dictionary</i>, pp. 222, 223.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001153": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001153",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001154": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001154",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">392</$link></sup> Pigafetta evidently means the Chinese by the Lequians who are known to have carried on trade for many years with the Philippines, and who indeed, once owned them.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001155": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001155",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001156": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001156",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p>Following this paragraph in the Italian MS. (folio 40a) is the chart of Caghaiam (<i>q.v.</i>, p. 202). This chart is shown on folio 53b in MS. 5,650, preceded by the words: “Below is shown the island of Caghaian.” <a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a></p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001157": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001157",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001158": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001158",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">393</$link></sup> MS. 5,650 does not mention the cuirasses.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001159": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001159",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001160": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001160",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">394</$link></sup> Eden reads: “40. leagues.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001161": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001161",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001162": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001162",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">395</$link></sup> Albo (Navarrete, iv, p. 221) says: “We left that place [<i>i.e.</i>, Quipit] and sailed west southwest, southwest, and west, until we came to an island containing very few inhabitants and called Quagayan. We anchored in the northern part of that island, where we asked for the location of the island of Poluan, in order to get provisions of rice, for that island contains it in abundance, and many ships are laden there for other districts. Accordingly we sailed west northwest and came across the headland of the island of Poluan.” The “Roteiro” (Stanley, p. 14) calls Cagaiam, Caram. It is the island of Cagayan Sulu, which lies northeast of Borneo.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001163": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001163",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001164": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001164",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">396</$link></sup> The “Roteiro” (Stanley, p. 15) says that the ships contained only sufficient provisions for a week.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001165": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001165",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001166": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001166",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">397</$link></sup> Eden reads: “C.lxxix. degrees and a third parte.” MS. 5,650 reads: “one hundred and sixty-one and one-third degrees.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001167": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001167",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001168": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001168",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">398</$link></sup> Occurrences at Palawan are given as follows by Albo (Navarrete, iv, pp. 221, 222): “Then we sailed north by east along the coast [of Palawan] until we reached a village called Saocao, where we made peace. Its inhabitants were Moros. We went to another village of Cafres, where we bartered for a considerable quantity of rice, and consequently laid in a good supply of provisions. That coast extends northeast and southwest. The headland of its northeastern part lies in 9 and one-third degrees, and that of the southwestern part in 8 and one-third degrees. Then on returning to the southwest quite to the headland of this island, we found an island near which is a bay. In this course and along Poluan many shoals are found. This headland lies east and west with Quipit and northeast by east and southwest by west with Quagayan.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001169": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001169",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001170": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001170",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p>The “Roteiro” (Stanley, pp. 15–17) gives a fuller account of occurrences at Palawan. At the first settlement at which they attempt to land, the natives prove hostile, whereupon they go toward another island, but contrary weather compelling them to anchor near Palawan, they are invited ashore on that island by the people of another village. There one of the soldiers, Joam de Campos, lands alone in order to get provisions. Being received kindly at this port, named Dyguasam (perhaps Puerto Princesa), the people set about preparing provisions for the strangers. Then going to another nearby village, where Carvalho makes peace with the chief, provisions of rice, goats, and swine are bought. At the latter village, a Portuguese-speaking negro who has been baptized at the Moluccas, is met, who promises <a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a>to guide them to Borneo, but he fails them at the last moment. Capturing a prau and three Moros near the former village, they are guided to Borneo. Brito (Navarrete, iv, p. 309) says that the two ships remained a month in Palawan, “a rich country, where they got new directions about Burneo, and captured two men to guide them there.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001171": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001171",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001172": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001172",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p>At this point in the Italian MS. (folio 41a) follows the chart of Sundan and Pulaoam (<i>q.v.</i>, p. 210). MS. 5,650 shows it on folio 54b, where it is preceded by the words: “Chart of the island of Pulaoan and the port of Tegozzao.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001173": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001173",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001174": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001174",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">399</$link></sup> MS. 5,650 reads: “all.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001175": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001175",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001176": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001176",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">400</$link></sup> This passage is defective in MS. 5,650, where it reads as follows: “They have bows with wooden arrows more than one palmo long, some of which are pointed with long sharp fishbones, poisoned with poisonous herbs, while others are tipped with poisoned bamboo.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001177": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001177",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001178": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001178",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">401</$link></sup> MS. 5,650 reads: “mace.” Jannetone as pointed out by Mosto (p. 85, note 4) was a missile weapon.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001179": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001179",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001180": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001180",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">402</$link></sup> Cockfighting is still the great diversion of the Malays and Malasian peoples. See Wallace’s <i>Malay Archipelago</i> (New York, 1869), p. 477; and Bowring’s <i>Visit to Philippine Isles</i> (London, 1859). pp. 149–153.</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001181": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001181",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001182": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001182",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">403</$link></sup> Eden reads: “fyue leaques.”</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001183": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001183",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001184": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001184",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-0d454f twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-5fae15 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-1a3ef0 twpub-c6b43ad861391ea7-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"back\"><div class=\"div1 notes\"><div class=\"divBody\"><p><sup><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000000171\">404</$link></sup> From the Spanish word <i>almadia</i>, (a sort of canoe used by the inhabitants of the East Indies; also a boat used by the Portuguese and their slaves in the East Indies: generally of one single tree, although there are various kinds, to one of which is given the name <i>coche</i>, “carriage”) which is derived from the Arabic <i>al-madia</i> or <i>almadiya</i>, from the root <i>adar</i>, “to cross,” so called because those vessels are used in crossing rivers.—Echegaray’s <i>Dic. etimológico</i> (Madrid, 1887).</p></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001185": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/c6b43ad861391ea7/text/000001185",
